SIMPLE: ethos
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ethos
<hw>E"thos</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/
character. See <er>Ethic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The character,
sentiment, or disposition of a community or people, considered as a
natural endowment; the spirit which actuates manners and customs; also,
the characteristic tone or genius of an institution or social
organization.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(esthetics)</fld> <def>The traits in a work of art
which express the ideal or typic character -- character as influenced by
the <xex>ethos</xex> (sense 1) of a people -- rather than realistic or
emotional situations or individual character in a narrow sense; --
opposed to <contr>pathos</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ethule</ent>⟦br⟧
